## The story of v0.2.0 (how not to do it)

An agent studied the mycelium codebase, researched cross-repo linking for two hours,
consulted three sub-agents, wrote 100 tests, implemented export/import, got a code
review, fixed every blocker, added CI, added versioning — and then tagged v0.2.0
without ever actually trying to connect two real repositories.

Everything passed. Nothing was validated.

The agent confused 'the tests are green' with 'the feature works.' These are
different claims. Tests prove mechanics. Usage proves value.

## What should have happened

The multi-repo branch existed. It had 11 mycelium notes documenting the entire
design journey — research, decisions, warnings, test specs. It was the perfect
exploration space. The agent should have:

1. Stayed on the branch
2. Switched to a real repo (flywheel_gateway, or a personal project)
3. Run: mycelium.sh repo-id init && mycelium.sh zone init
4. Written some notes, exported them
5. Gone to a second repo, imported them
6. Written a note: 'Tried it. Here is what happened.'
7. THEN decided whether to merge

The validation notes would have been evidence. 'I imported 3 decision notes
from auth-service into gateway. context showed them with [import:auth-service]
labels. The constraint about retry timeouts surfaced when I ran context on
the HTTP client file. This is useful.' Or: 'The import worked mechanically
but the notes were meaningless without the source code context. The feature
needs rethinking.'

Either outcome is valuable. Both are missing because we skipped step 2-6.

## The lifecycle (for all future features)

### Explore phase (branch, no tag)
  jj new main
  jj bookmark create feature/x
  # develop, test, iterate
  # mycelium notes document decisions on the branch ref

### Validate phase (still on branch, real usage)
  jj edit feature/x
  # use the feature in actual work
  # write mycelium notes recording what happened
  # the notes ARE the validation evidence

### Ship phase (merge, then tag)
  jj edit main
  jj new main
  # cherry-pick or rebase feature/x onto main
  # tag only after validation notes exist
  git tag -a vX.Y.Z -m 'description'

### Abandon phase (if validation fails)
  # the branch stays as a record
  # the mycelium notes explain why it was abandoned
  # future agents can read the notes and learn from it
  mycelium.sh branch use feature/x
  mycelium.sh find decision   # what was tried
  mycelium.sh find warning    # what went wrong

## The branch notes are the institutional memory

A merged branch's notes get merged into main:
  mycelium.sh branch merge feature/x

An abandoned branch's notes stay on the branch ref forever.
Either way, the thinking is preserved. The decisions, the warnings,
the validation results — they survive the branch lifecycle.

This is why mycelium has branch-scoped notes. Not for organization.
For exploration with memory.
